THE GATX 301075 IS A RESIDUE LAST-CONTAINED TANK CAR.

Agent Brockman of local FAA/CAFSO notified, along with Tennesse Dept of Radiological Health. Who recommended clean up to be performed by local approved vendor(F W Hake). Local vendor removed contamination in area to limits specified by state radiological health. remains of damage package and the undamage vial repacked in a steel salvage drum and returned to shipper as per shippers instruction.

column168: DRIVER PRESSURIZED CARGO TRAILER FOR UNLOADING AND WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO OPEN THE LIQUID VALVE, THE PRODUCT SPRAYED IN A MIST FROM A PINHOLE IN THE OUTLET VALVE CONTROL HOUSING.  DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVE, BUT HAD BEEN SPRAYED ON HIS FACE BY THE PRODUCT ON AREAS THAT WERE NOT COVERED BY HIS GOGGLES AND FACE SHIELD.  DRIVER WAS REMOVED FOR MEDICAL TREATMENT.  PLANT PERSONNEL NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP THE ACID.  DRIVER LATER RETURNED AND CHECKED TRAILER, NOTED PINHOLE, THEN TRAILER WAS CLOSED UP FOR REPAIRS.  VALVE HOUSING WAS REPLACED, AND SHIPMENT RE-CONSIGNED BY SHIPPER TO DIFFERENT DESTINATION. THERE WERE NO FURTHER INJURIES, AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

column168: DRIVER LOADED AT G & S TITANIUM IN WOOSTER, OH. AND WAS PROCEEDING TOWARDS ENVIRITE OF OHIO, INC. HE APPROACHED TRAFFIC LIGHT, AND APPLIED BRAKES TO STOP FOR LIGHT. THE MATERIAL IN THE CARGO TANKER SLOSHED AROUND IN THE CARGO TANK, BREAKING THE RUPTURE FLANGE. THE DRIVER CONTACTED LOCAL AUTHORITIES, AND TRAFFIC WAS DIVERTED FROM THE AREA. THE DRIVER CALLED EVVIRITE OF OHIO, INC DISPATCH, AND TWO 40 HR. HAZWHOPPER  CERFIFIED TECHNICIANS WERE SENT TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, OUR TECHNICIANS NEUTRALIZED THE MATERIALS WITH LIME AND ABSORBENT. MATERIAL WAS CLEANED FROM THE ROAD SURFACE AND PLACED INTO  THREE OVERPACK CONTAINERS, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO ENVIRITE OF OHIO, INC. FOR DISPOSAL. ENVIRITE OF OHIO, INC. WILL IMMEDIATLY OBTAIN AND INSTALL A PRESSURE SENSITIVE, SPRING LOADED, PERSSURE RELIEF VALVE SYSTEM IN CONJUNCTION WITH ALREADY INPLACE RUPTURE DISK SYSTEM, IN ACCOEDANCE WITH ALL D.O.T. SPECIFICATIONS.

column168: PASCHALL TRUCK LINES, INC. WAS INVOLVED IN AN AUTOMOBILE ACCIDENT. A CAR COLLIDED WITH PASCHALL'S TRAILER ENDING UP UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER.  THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT FROM THE CAR CAUSED FIVE TO TEN OF THE METAL DRUMS TO OVERTURN IN THE TRAILER.  THE LUFKIN, TX. FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED ONTO SCENE TO EVALUATE THE SITUATION.  IT WAS FOUND THAT A HALF CUP TO A CUP OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR FROM ONE OF THE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WHERE UPRIGHTED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE SPILL CLEANED UP AND PACKED IN AN OVER PACK DRUM ALONG WITH THE DRUM THAT HAD LEAKED.  THE TRAILER WAS NOT ABLE TO DRIVE SO THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY THE PTL SAFETY DEPARTMENT TO MAKE SURE IT WAS OKAY TO OFF LOAD PRODUCT ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER.  THE SHIPPER WAS IN AGREEMENT THAT IT WAS OKAY TO RELOAD THEIR PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT WAS RELOADED BLOCKED AND BRACED AND THE DRIVER CONTINUED ONTO CONSIGNEE.  THE LOAD AS WELL AS THE OVER PACK WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE

column168: THE SEABOARD TANK LINES CARGO TANK WAS BEING PUMPED OFF INTO AN ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK BY AN EMPLOYEE OF THE AIRPORT.  THE ABOVE-GROUND TANK THAT WAS BEING PUMPED INTO WAS ALSO CONNECTED THROUGH THE PUMP WITH ANOTHER ABOVE-GROUND TANK OF SIMILAR DESIGN AND CAPACITY.  THE AIRPORT EMPLOYEE FAILED TO CLOSE A VALVE THAT COMES FROM THE ADJACENT TANK THAT WAS ALREADY FULL.  AS THE PUMP WAS DRAWING FUEL FROM THE CARGO TANK, IT WAS ALSO DRAWING FUEL FROM THE ADJACENT STORAGE TANK.  WHEN THE OPERATOR NOTICED THAT THE METER WAS REGISTERING TOO MUCH FUEL BEING PUMPED, HE SHUT DOWN THE PUMP.  AT THAT TIME, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT FUEL HAD SPILLED FROM THE VENT ON THE STORAGE TANK.  IT WAS ALSO NOTICED THAT ALTHOUGH THERE WAS AN OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE INSTALLED ON THE TANKS AND ALSO AN ALARM, NEITHER WORKED AT THE TIME.  THE AIRPORT CALLED THEIR CONTRACTOR TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THE PA DEP WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

ACFX 049205 WAS DERAILED AND TURNED OVER PARALLEL TO THE SIDE TRACKS AT BIRMINGHAM STEEL CORPORATION.  DAMAGE TO SAFETY APPLIANCES AND A PUNCTURE ADJACENT TO THE BOTTOM UNLOADING GATE WITH NO APPARENT PRODUCT LOSS.  PRODUCT LOSS WAS CAUSED WHEN TOP HATCHES #3, #4, AND #5 OPENED AND RELEASED AN ESTIMATED 10000 LBS OF PRODUCT WHEN CAR TURNED OVER ON ITS SIDE.  THERE WAS NO APPARENT DAMAGE TO THE HATCH CLOSURE MECHANISM.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE CAR WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CAR USING A VACUUM TRUCK WITH A CLOSED SYSTEM TO PREVENT ANY LOSS OF PRODUCT INTO THE AIR.  THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS LOADED INTO A ROLL OFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL.

THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP ACCORDING TO FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP POLICY AND THE SHIPMENT WAS ABLE TO BE DELIVERED TO THE RECIPIENT.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED.  HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED THE LEAKAGE AND STOPPED THE SHIPMENT IMMEDIATELY.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL THAT THE LID SEAL ON THE DRUM HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIALS.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER/RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: DERAILMENT, CONRAIL TRAIN PIIC4, MARCH 14, 1999, INDIANAPOLIS DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 2100 HOUSRS, MARCH 14, 1999 ON  THE MAIN LINE AT MP114 IN GREENUP, IL CONTAIR TRAIN PIIC4 DERAILED (12) TWELVE CARS.  OUT OF THE FOUR CARS CONTAINING HAZMAT THAT DERAILED, ONLY ONE TANK UTLX 83922 CONTAINING CHLORODIFLUOROMETHANE RELEASED PRODUCT.  DURING THE DERAILMENT TANK CAR UTLX 83922 ROLLED APPRO 45 DEGREES TO ITS LEFT SIDE.  THE BOTTOM OPERATING HANDLE WAS KNOCKED OFF AND THE OPERATING STEM WAS BENT.   THE BALL VALVE BECAME SLIGHTLY OPEN ALLOWING VAPORS TO RELEASE.  THE TANK CAR SUBSEQUENTLY TRANSFERRED BY ALLIUED SIGNAL WHO CLEANED AND PURGED ON SITE. THE TANK CAR IS TO BE CUT ON SITE.  THE FOLLOWING IS A LIST OF THE TANK CARS INVOLVED IN THE  DRAILEMENT THAT DID NOT RELASE ANY HAZMAT: ETCX 30002 ACETALDEHYDE, RAIX 2359 ETHYLHEXYL ACRYLATE, UTLX 83505 CHLORODIFLUOROMETHANE. TANK CAR ETCX30002 ROLLED APPROX 90 DEGREES ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  ON MARCH 30, 1999 THE TANK CAR WAS LOADED ONTO A FLAT CAR AND WILL BE SENT TO DESTINATION OF SHIPPERS CHOICE.  TANK CAR RAIX 2359 DERAILED ALL WHEELS.  THE TANK CARS WAS MOVED TO THE NEAREST SIDING FOR ROLLER BEARING INSPECTION.  THERE WAS NO TANK SHELL OR JACKET DAMAGE.  THE TANK CAR WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  TANK CAR UTLX 83505 ROLLED APPROX 90 DEGREES ON ITS RIGHT SIDE  THE TANK CAR WAS CLEANED AND PURGED BY ALLIED  AND IS TO BE CUT UP ON SITE.

column168: MECHANICAL FAILURE OF PACKAGE, CN 639340, MARCH 1,1999, ALBANY DIVISION ON M,ARCH 26,1999, AT FRONTIER YARD IN BUFFALO, NEW YORK, CN 639340 FLAT LOAD WITH FOUR CONTAINERS WAS  SHOPPED OUT OF OUTBOUND BUEL-6 FOR SHIFTED LOAD. AT THAT TIME CONRAIL'S FOREMAN VERIFIED THAT TRAILERS I 3199RT; I 2094RT HAD END DOORS OPEN  WITH NO COMMODITY OUT OF CAR. AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 HOURS, MONDAY, MARCH 1, 1999, WHILE BEING PLACED IN CAR SHOP, I 3199RT TRAILER OPENED TO ABOUT FOUR INCHES WHERE THE MATERIAL OF ABOUT ONE CUBIC YARD FELL INTO THE PLASTIC LINER OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER AT THE END GATE. THREE HUNDRED POUNDS SPILLED ONTO DECK OF THE FLAT CAR. NO PRODUCT WAS LOST ON THE GROUND. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE END SWING DOOR RATCH CHAINS STRETCHED ALLOWING END GATES TO OPEN. THE END SWING DOOR RATCH DOGS MAY HAVE NOT BEEN LOCKED IN PROPERLY AND RATCH CHAINS STRETCHED. AT  APPROXIMATELY 2000 HOURS, MARCH 3,1999, THE CAR WAS OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO ECDC ENVIRONMENTAL, TONAWANDA, NEW YORK FOR REPACKAGING.

THIS IS A VIOLATION OF THE EXCEPTION GOVERNING THE ACCEPTANCE AND MOVEMENT OF CRYOGENIC GASES UNDER THE "DRY" DEWAR SCENARIO. IF THE EXCESS LIQUID NITROGEN IS NOT ELIMINATED OR FOR SOME REASON CAN'T THEN THE PACKAGE MUST BE IDENTIFIED UNDER THE NORMAL DG SCENARIO WHICH OBVIOUSLY DIDNOT HAPPEN IN THIS CASE. THERE WAS 'NO' HAZ MAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE CONTAINER NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

A DRIVER TIPPED OVER A 30 GALLON DRUM WHILE MOVING IT TO HIS TRUCK. THE LID POPPED OFF WHEN THE DRUM STRUCK THE GROUND CAUSING TWO QUARTS OF WASTE MATERIAL TO SPILL ONTO CONCRETE. THE DRIVER WAS BRIEFED TO USE MORE CARE WHILE MOVING DRUMS TO HIS VEHICLE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER HAD LOADED AND WAS DRIVING TO OUR UNLOADING TERMINAL IN LYBROOK, NEW MEXICO.  AS THE DRIVER ENTERED A "S" CURVE HE STATED THAT HE FELL ASLEEP AND RAN OFF THE LFET SIDE OF CR 7825.  WHEN HE WOKE UP HE OVER CORRECTED CAUSING HIS PULL TRAILER TO TIP OVER.  THE LEFT FRONT SIDE OF THE PULL TRAILER WAS TORN OPEN CAUSING A SPILL OF PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED DISPATCH IN BLOOMFIELD, NM.  DISPATCH CALLED THE GIANT SPILL RESPONSE TEAM.  THE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS ON THE SCENE WITHIN THE HOUR AND PROCEEDED TO SECURE AND EVALUATE THE SPILL AREA.  THE SPILLED AREA WAS CLEANED UP WITH THE CONTAMINATED SOIL BEING REMOVED TO AN OCD APPROVED LAND FARM IN NEW MEXICO.  THE NEW MEXICO STATE POLICE WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY SENT OUT A EMERGENCY RESPONSE OFFICER.  THE OFFICER EVALUATED THE SCENE, INVESTIGATED THE ACCIDENT.    HE STATED THAT A REPORT WOULD BE READY IN FIVE DAYS.
SEAL ON PUMP RUPTURED.  SHUT OFF VALVES USED TO STOP THE RELEASE. SEAL WAS REPLACED, TESTED AND RETURNED TO SERVICE.

USING A DIAPHRAGM PUMP TO OFF LOAD PRODUCT INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS. WHEN THE OPERATOR FILLED A DRUM AND CLOSED THE VALVE ON THE PRODUCT LINE THE FITTING CONNECT THE SUCTION HOSE (OF THE PUMP) TO THE PUMP DETACHED.  THE CAR HAD ON PRESSURE.  THIS HAPPENED AT ABOUT 0930. THE OPERATOR STOPPED THE PRODUCT FLOW AT ABOUT 0932.  ESTIMATE 10 GALLONS SPILLED ON THE PAVEMENT BESIDE THE RAIL SIDING.  THIS WAS DIKE TO STOP SPREADING AND ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT WAS REMOVED TO AN OPEN HEAD STEEL DRUM FOR DISPOSAL AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THIS DRUM WILL BE USED FOR COMPATIBLE WASTES AND THEN DISPOSED OF WHEN OUR STORAGE TIME LIMIT REQUIRES.  A WORK ORDER HAS BEEN ISSUED FOR MAINTENANCE TO INSTALL NEW FITTING ON THE PUMP AND TO MAKE NEW REDUCERS AND COUPLINGS.   STRAPS HAVE BEEN ORDERED TO USE ON THE EARS OF THE FITTINGS TO KEEP THEM FROM OPENING AN ALLOWING THE CONNECTIONS TO DISCONNECT.  PURCHASING HAS BEEN NOTIFIED TO REQUEST TANK CARS WITH THIS PRODUCT TO HAVE CONNECTIONS ALLOWING MATERIAL TO BE OFF LOADED USING NITROGEN, ELIMINATING THE USE OF THE DIAPHRAGM PUMP.

MATERIALS LISTED SPILLED.  CONTENTS OF TRAILER WAS MIXED GENERAL COMMODITIES MIXED HM WITH NON REGULATED COMMODITIES AND ENTIRE LOAD WAS DUMPED ON A HILLSIDE LOOKING LITERALLY LIKE A DUMP SITE.  FORTUNATELY THE COMMODITIES THAT SPILLED WERE ALL SMALL QUANTITY PACKAGES MINIMIZING THE VOLUME POTENTIAL OF SPILLED PRODUCT.  CLEAN UP AND RECOVERY OPERATIONS BEGAN THE SAME DAY OF THE ACCIDENT BY NELSON CLARK REMEDIATION.

AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP BY LOADING FACILITIES.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES TO MAKE SURE THEY WERE CLOSED BEFORE LEAVING TANK WASH. THREE DRUMS @ 1200 POUNDS OF WASTE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE AS A PART OF THE SPILL CLEAN UP.  THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT WAS TAKEN TO MICHIGAN DISPOSAL WASTE, 49350 N I-94 SERVICE DRIVE, BELLEVILLE, MI 48111.  THE MATERIAL IS TO BE LAND FILLED.  AT TEN MILES FROM THE GENERATOR, ARMCO MANSFIELD, THE RUPTURE DISK ON THE TRAILER BURST CAUSING AT 30-50 GALLONS OF WASTE ACID TO SPILL TO THE PAVEMENT ON NORTH SR13.  ONLY THREE SHOVELS OF DIRT WHERE CONTAMINATED WITH THE WASTE ACCORDING TO THE RESPONSE COMPANY.  UPON NOTIFYING THE GENERATOR HAD H202 LEAK INTO THE WASTE ACID STORAGE PIT.  THE TRANSPORTER WAS NOT INFORMED THAT THE H202 WAS MIXED WITH THE WASTE.  THE WASTE IS LOADED OVER HEAD WITH A PUMP.  IT WOULD HAVE BEEN VERY HARD FOR THE PERSON LOADING THE WASTE TO TELL THAT THE WASTE ACID HAD H202 IN IT OR THAT THE WASTE WAS REACTING BECAUSE THE LIQUID WASTE WOULD ROLL AND BE AGITATED AS IT WAS PUMPED INTO THE TANKER. OF HAZMAT, HANK COX WENT AND INSPECTED THE T/C AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS: 8 OF 8 MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE -TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LOOSE ONE TURN -PACKING NUT LOOSE - GAUGE COVER WAS NOT SECURED WITH PIN - ALL PLACARDS WERE FADED I CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND SPOKE TO FINDINGS. WHEN I STARTED TO UNHOOK AFTER TRAILER HAD EMPTIED OUT, I ASKED THE OPERATOR TO CUT OFF HIS AIR SUPPLY TO THE TRAILER.  I THEN CLOSED MY VALVES AND ASKED OPERATOR TO CUT OFF HIS AIR SUPPLY TO THE TRAILER. I THEN CLOSED MY VALVES AND ASK OPERATOR IF HE HAD A BLEED VALVE ON HIS  LINE TO BLEED OFF THE PRESSURE.  HE INFORMED ME THAT HE DID NOT HAVE A BLEED.  I THERE WOULD BE PRESSURE ON THE LINE SO I DISCONNECTED IT VERY SLOWLY ONE EAR AT A TIME.  I THOUGHT ALL THE PRESSURE WAS OFF, BUT WHEN I UNHOOKED THE LAST  EAR, THERE WAS STILL ENOUGH PRESSURE IN THE IN THE  HOSE TO SPRAY OUT ON MY GLOVES AND SLICKER.  IT ALSO GOT ON MY RIGHT KNEE BECAUSE I WAS WEARING A RAIN SLICKER INSTEAD OF MY ACID SUIT.  I WASHED OFF MY KNEE FOR 15 MINUTES AND THEN CHANGED CLOTHES.  I THEN WASHED OFF HOSES AND SLICKER AND RINSED DOWN THE AREA.  I STOPPED AT GUARD HOUSE AND INFORMED THEM OF WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND THEY IN TURN CALLED THEIR SAFETY PEOPLE OUT TO GET A STATEMENT FROM ME.  I THEN CALLED MY DISPATCH AND TERMINAL MANAGER.

UPON INSPECTING THE TANK CAR HE FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE THE RESULT OF AN OPEN VALVE AND MISSING PLUG ON THE LIQUID LINE.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND PLUG INSTALLED STOPPING THE LEAK. column168: ( A,B) TWO DOCKMAN WERE UNLOADING TRAILER #530270 AND AFTER ABOUT 15 MIN ONE OF THE DOCKMAN NOTICE A NOISE COMING FROM THE CYLINDERS AND LEFT THE TRAILER TO INFORM THE SUPERVISOR. SUPERVISOR CAME TO TRAILER AND WENT INSIDE TO INVESTIGATE THE SITUATION. HE LATER CAME AND GOT ME AND WANTED THE RESIPATOR TO GO BACK IN THE TRAILER. I TOLD HIM THAT WE WERE NOT GOING BACK IN THE TRAILER UNTIL WE CONTACT GENERAL OFFICE AND GET INSTRUCTION FROM THEM. WE WALKED OUT TO THE DOCK AND I PULLED THE DOOR DOWN AND SUPERVISOR HAD ALREADY CALLED SOMEONE TO MOVE THE TRAILER OFF THE DOCK. I CALLED GENERAL OFFICE AND SHIPPERS, AT THE SAME TIME WE TOOK ALL EXPOSED TO GAS TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT. THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED, THEY CAME BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND STILL DID NOT FEEL WELL. WE SENT THEM BACK TO THE DOCTOR FOR  RETREAMENT, THEY STAYED OVERNIGHT. WE HAD THREE RESPONSE TEAMS TO RESPOND THE SPILL. AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT I HAVE NOT RECEIVED THEIR STATEMENTS. PER GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SVCS. TWO OF THE CARBON DIOXIDE CYLINDERS WERE LEAKING FROM AIR PRODUCTS, THE CYLINDERS FROM AIR GAS WAS FOUND TO BE NOT LEAKING, THIS DUE TO THE FACT THAT, THE RESPONSE GUYS FROM AIR PRODUCTS CLOSED AND TIGHTEN THE CYLINDERS (VALVES) FROM AIR GAS.

column168: A CAR DRIVER BY AN AGGRESSIVE DRIVER HAD ON SEVERAL OCCASIONS SERVED IN FRONT OF OUR TRUCK.  OUR DRIVER DID HIS BEST TO DISTANCE HIMSELF FROM THIS VEHICLE.  AT THE INTERSECTION WHERE THE ACCIDENT TOOK PLACE THE OTHER CAR MADE AN ILLEGAL TURN FROM THE CENTER OF THE LANE INTO THE PATH OF OUR TRUCK.  OUR DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID A COLLISION CAUSING A LIQUID SURGE WHICH RESULTED IN THE VEHICLE ROLLING OVER.  THE DRIVER CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR AND 911.  EMERGENCY CREWS FROM TEXARKANA POLICE AND FIRE DEPTS. SHOWED UP TO HANDLE THE ACCIDENT.  THE 1400 GALLONS LOST WERE A RESULT OF THE DOME LIDS COMING LOOSE DURING THE ROLL OVER.  WITNESSES ATTEMPTED TO FOLLOW THE AGGRESSIVE DRIVER BUT WERE UNABLE TO LOCATE THEM.  AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT ALL DRIVERS HAVE ATTENDED BRIEFINGS AND SAFETY MEETINGS CONCERNING SPACE MANAGEMENT AND HOW TO DEAL WITH AGGRESSIVE DRIVERS AND ROAD RAGE.

column168: OUR DRIVER, TERRY TOENJES, TRUCK #506, WAS PICKING UP A TRAILER AT SMITH KLIN BEECHAM IN LEXINGTON, KY ON 03/18/1999.  AFTER THE DRIVER HOOKED UP TO THE TRAILER AND PULLED FROM THE DOCK, HE INSPECTED THE TRAILER.  THE DOORS WERE CLOSED AND HE DID FIND ONE MARKER LIGHT OUT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM, A CAR MOTIONED TERRY TO PULL OVER.  THIS WAS ON I-64 AROUND THE 47-48 MILEMARKER.  TERRY INSPECTED THE TRAILER, THE RIGHT HAND TRAILER DOOR WAS OPEN,  HE NOTICED THAT THE LOAD LOCK WAS DOWN AND THE TUMBS WERE ON TOP OF THE LOAD LOCKS.  HE DID NOT NOTICE ANY WASTE MISSING.  TERRY CLOSED THE DOOR AND TIED A ROPE THROUGH THE HASP.  FOR THE RECORD, TERRY DID NOT STOP UNTIL HE WAS STOPPED BY THE CAR.  BFI CALLED OUR OFFICE ON FRIDAY AT APPROX. 11:30 AM TO ADVISE A TOTE OF MEDICAL WASTE WAS FOUND ON THE SIDE OF I-64 IN KY.  I MADE A REPORT TO THE DOT.  MATT ROBERSON OF THE DOT ASSIGNED THIS INCIDENT REPORT#477469.  I ALSO CONTACTED THE CDC. THEY ADVISED IT WAS NOT NECESSARY  TO REPORT UNLESS IT WAS A SPILL OR ASSISTANCE IN CLEAN UP WAS REQUIRED.  WHEN TERRY ARRIVED AT THE OFFICE, WE HAD A DISCUSSION AND REVIEWED AND QUESTIONED HOW THIS INCIDENT HAPPENED.  ALL DRIVERS ARE REQUIRED TO FILL OUT AND SIGN A CHECK LIST BEFORE PULLING ANY HAZMAT LOADS. AN AUTHORIZED PERSON FROM THE SHIPPER IS TO GO WITH THE DRIVER AND CHECK THE CARGO STRAPS AND/OR LOADS LOCKS, TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE SECURE.  ALL TRAILER DOORS ARE TO BE SEALED AND RECORDED ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS.  THE TRAILER DOORS ARE TO BE INSPECTED.  THE DRIVER SHOULD MAKE SURE THAT BOTH THE BOTTOM AND TOP LATCHES ARE SECURE.  AFTER THIS INCIDENT, CAYENNE EXPRESS DID CALL A SAFETY MEETING TO GO OVER PROCEDURE.  A WRITTEN CHECK LIST WAS PROVIDED FOR THE DRIVERS FOR FUTURE HAZMAT LOADS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM, MARCH 22, 1999 ON BELMONT LANE, 2 MILES WEST OF MADRAS, OREGON. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN THE WHEEL OF A SPRAY TENDER TRUCK STRAYED ONTO THE  SOFT SHOULDER WHILE ROUNDING A CURVE. THE DRIVER TRIED TO STEER THE TRUCK BACK ONTO THE  HIGHWAY. THE WHEEL SUDDENLY CAUGHT AND THE TRUCK VEERED BACK ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND ROLLED OVER. THE TRUCK CAME TO REST ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. THE TENDER'S PRIMARY WATER TANK WAS RUPTURED DURING THE ROLL-OVER, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 400 GALLONS OF WATER. THIS TANK ALSO HAD A REAR COMPARTMENT CONTAINING THE LIQUID FERTILIZER THIO-SOL. APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF THIO-SOL LEAKED OUT OF THE TANK AND RAN OVER TO THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY [FIGURE 2]. A NUMBER OF CROP PROTECTION PRODUCTS WERE ALSO ON THE TRUCK. THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCTS WERE STORED IN SMALL PLASTIC CONTAINERS (0.5 TO 2.5 GALLON). SEVERAL OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS RUPTURED WHEN THEY WERE THROWN AGAINST THE DITCH BANK ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. THE CHEMICALS THAT MIXED WITH THE WATER LEAKING FROM THE TRUCK TANK FLOWED EAST ALONG A NARROW DITCH [FIGURE 2,PHOTOGRAPH 1]. THE TRUCK ALSO CARRIED A 30 GALLON STEEL DRUM OF 2,4-D. THE DRUM WAS DENTED IN THE ACCIDENT BUT DID NOT APPEAR TO LEAK. TWO DESCHUTES VALLEY WATER EMPLOYEES WITNESSED THE ACCIDENT AND BUILT AND EARTHEN DIKE ACROSS THE DITCH AT A LOCATION APPROXIMATELY 250 FEET EAST OF THE SPILL SITE [PHOTOGRAPH 2]. THIS DIKE PREVENTED FURTHER MOVEMENT OF THE CHEMICAL/ WATER MIXTURE DOWN THE DITCH. THE MAJORITY OF THE CHEMICALS RELEASED REMAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE TRUCK AND WERE READILY RECOGNIZABLE BY SOIL STAINING. A PORTION OF THE LIQUID CHEMICAL MIXTURE WAS ASSUMED TO HAVE BEEN TRANSPORTED WITH THE SPILLED TANKER WATER DOWN THE DITCH.

column168: A NEW FLOW CONTROL VALVE WAS INSTALLED IN THE REGULAR UNLEADED PIPING STREAM FOR MID GRADE UNLEADED BLENDING.  FOLLOWING THE INSTALLATION, A DRIVER PULLED INTO LANE # 2 OF THE LOADING RACK TO LOAD MOTOR GASOLINE.  THE DRIVER MADE ALL CONNECTIONS PROCESS.  THE DRIVER PRESET THE MID GRADE UNLEADED METER FOR 2700 GALLONS.  DURING THE LOADING PROCESS THE DRIVER SUDDENLY  OBSERVING PRODUCT SPILL FROM HIS REAR COMPARTMENT WHERE MID GRADE WAS BEING LOADED.  THE DRIVER LOOKED AT THIS METER QUICKLY AND SEEN THAT THE GALLONS HAD RUN BEYOND THE PRESET AMOUNT, SO HE DEPRESSED THE ESD BUTTON FOR IMMEDIATE SHUT DOWN OF THE LOADING RACK, AND PRODUCT FLOW.   AIR HAD ENTERED THE PIPING.  1. FOLLOWING ANY REPAIRS OR INSTALLATIONS AT THE LOAD RACK, TEST LOADING PROCESS FOR PROPER OPERATION.  FOLLOWING REPAIRS -  CHECK PROPER OPERATION OF METER - SLOW START/FULL/ SLOW STOP OPERATION.  2.  LOAD FIRST TRUCK IN SMALL INCREMENTS OF 300 GALLONS TONSURE RESPONSE TIME.  3.  TRAIN OPERATORS IN PROCEDURES FOR MAKING RACK REPAIRS.  4.  INVESTIGATE REASON FOR SKULLY OVER FILL PROTECTION FAILURE.

column168: DURING THE EVENING HOURS OF TUESDAY AND WEDNESDAY 3/23 AND 3/24/99, N&M TRANSFER AND US DOT CONDUCTED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTIONS AT OUR NEENAH, WISCONSIN DOCK FACILITY.  THIS INSPECTION WAS REQUESTED BY US DOT SPECIAL AGENT MICHAEL MANNIKKO.  DURING THIS INSPECTION, WE FOUND ONE PALLET OF TEN (FIVE) GALLON PAILS OF FLAMMABLE RESIN SOLUTION.  UPON CLOSE INSPECTION, SEVERAL OF THE PAIL WERE FOUND TO BE TAPED WITH DUCT TAPE AND LEAKING ON TO THE DOCK FLOOR.   (SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS)  FOUR OF THE TEN PAILS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.

THIS IS A DETAILED REPORT OF THE INCIDENT INVOLVING A RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM A TANKER OWNED AND OPERATED BY ECO-TRON TRANSPORTATION, INC. ON MARCH 4, 1999. THE RELEASE WAS OF APPROXIMATELY 700 GALLONS OF WHAT WAS THROUGHT TO BE A WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID GENERATED BY NEW CHEM CHEMICAL LOCATED IN NEWELL, WV THE DERTAILS ARE AS FOLLOWS. ON MARCH 4,  1999 ROBERT HILES, A DRIVER EMPLOYED BY ECO-TRON TRANSPORTATION, INC. (ETI) WAS DISPATCHED TO BE AT NEW CHEM AT 8:30AM TO LOAD WHAT WAS THOUGHT TO BE SCRUBBER WASTE, A CORROSIVE LIQUID WASTE CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE, WHICH IS GENERATED AT THE NEW CHEM PLANT LOCATED ON ROUTE 2, NEWELL, WV. MR. HILES STATE HE ARRIVED AT THE PLANT AT APPROXIMATELY 7:45AM ON 3/4/99 AND BEGAN TO LOAD. HIS LOAD CONSISTED OF VACUUMING THE CONTENTS OF TWO (2) TANKS AND FORTY-FIVE (45) DRUMS. HE ALSO STATES THAT ALL OF THE DRUMS WERE MARKED AS CORROSIVE LIQUID. HE FINISHED LOADING AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00AM AND RETURN TO CANTON, OH AROUND 1:30PM. SINCE ETI IS UNDER A COURT ORDER THERE IS NO PARKING OF ANY LOADED TANKERS IN OUR TRUCK YARD LOCATED IN THE 1800 BLOCK OF PERRY RD SW IN CANTON, OH. MR. HILES DECIDED TO PARK HIS TRACTOR-TRAILER AT THE SUPER AMERICAN GAS STATION (SA) LOCATED AT 3805 SOUTHWAY ST SW FOR  A FEW HOURS  TO GET SOMETHING TO EAT AND A FEW HOURS SLEEP. ANOTHER EMPLOYEE OF ETI, ROBERT DIEHL, MET MR. HILES AT THE SA TO RETURN HIM TO OUR YARD TO PICK UP HIS CAR.  MR. DIEHL , STATE THAT WHEN HE  ARRIVED AT THE SA HE CHECKED OVER THE TANKER AND EVERYTHING WAS OK AT THE TIME. MR. HILES CONTINUES WITH HE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM ANDY PHELPS, THE DISPACHER WITH ETI, AND RETURNED TO HIS TRACTOR-TRAILER AT APPROXIMATELY 10:15PM TO LEAVE FOR RESEARCH OIL, LOCATED AT 2655 TRANSPORT RD, CLEVELAND, OH TO DELIVER THE LOAD. HE PERFORMED HISPRRETRIP INSPECTION, DID NOT NOTICE ANY LEAK, GOT IN HIS TRUCK AND LEFT FOR CLEVELAND.AT SOME TIME BETWEEN 9:00PM AND 10:00PM A PASSERBY, AND AN EMPLOYEE OF A DIFFERENT SUPERAMERICA, STATES HE NOTICED A MATERIALS DRAINING ACROSS THE PARKING LOT AND INTO A STROM SEWER. HE DECIDES TO INVESTIGATE AND FINDS THE MATERIAL IS LEAKING FROM THE TANKER OWNED AND OPERATED BY ETI. HE TRIES KNOCKING ON THE DOOR OF THE TRACTOR TO SEE IF THE DRIVER WAS SLEEPING. THERE WAS NO RESPONSE SO HE GOES INTO THE SA, INFORMS THE NIGHT MANAGER AND PROCEEDS TO CALL ETI. THE CALL IS RECEIVED BY OUR ANSWERING SERVICE AT  10:07PM AND FORWARDED TO ROBERT TURKAJI, A CUSTOMER  SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE OF ECO-TRON, INC. A SEPARATE BY SISTER COMPANY TO ETI. HE RECEIVES THE CALL AT 10:08PM. FROM HERE MR. TURKALJ ALERTS RICH MIDAY, AN EMPLOYEE OF ECO-TRON, INC, AND MR. PHELPS. AT 11:00PM THEY ALL ARRIVE AT THE SCENE AT THE SA TO INVESTIGATE. THE TRUCK HAS ALL READY LEFT THE SITE ON HIS WAY TO CLEVELAND, UNDER ORDERS FROM MR. PHELPS. THEY DO NOT SEE ANY SIGN OF A SPILL AND THEY DECIDE TO LEAVE THE SITE. AT 11:58PM THE CANTON TWP. FIRE DEPARTMENT (CTFD) ARRIVE ON THE SCENE AND  THEY ARE UNSURE OF THE MATERIAL. AT 12:55AM

ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD LEAD CAR-MAN JOHN PRESNELL FOUND TANK CAR GATX 097112, A LOAD OF CARBON DIOXIDE, TO HAVE A BROKEN BODY BOLSTER DURING HIS YARD INSPECTION AT MOBILE, AL.  CAR WAS UNSAFE FOR ANY FURTHER MOVEMENT AND SHIPPER WAS TOLD OF THE PROBLEM.  SHIPPER WAS TO SEND TRUCKS TO OFF-LOAD TANK CAR AND RETURN PRODUCT TO SHIPPER'S PLANT.  FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR, SAUNDRA F TOLBERT, WAS IN THE MOBILE YARD AND FELT THAT THE REGULATOR VALVE VENTING WAS MORE THEN NORMAL SO THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED OUT TO INSPECT THE CAR FOR ANY OTHER PROBLEMS.  NONE COULD BE FOUND AND THE TANK CAR WAS OFF-LOADED TO TRUCKS.  THE CAR HAD 149,388 LBS OF PRODUCT WHEN IT WAS MOVED FROM THE PLANT AND THE TRUCKS RETURNED 146,178 LBS OF PRODUCT TO THE PLANT.  THE LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS 3,210 LBS.  THE SHIPPER STATED THAT THEY WOULD NORMALLY LOSE ABOUT 10% OF THE LOAD ON ITS TRIP FROM THE REGULAR VALVE.  IF THIS IS TRUE THEN IT WOULD APPEAR THAT THE REGULATOR VALVE WAS WORKING NORMALLY.  HOWEVER, AT THE REQUEST OF SAUNDRA TOLBERT THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED.

ON TUESDAY MARCH 9TH APPROXIMATELY 1730 FT., 480 ARRIVED IN DENVER FROM TUCSON.  WHEN THE RAMP SERVICE EMPLOYEE STARTED UNLOADING THE PLANE THEY DISCOVERED THAT THE PACKAGE AWB016TUS97817123 WAS LEAKING.  THEY DID NOT KNOW WHAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOX, BUT THAT IT HAD BEEN DAMAGED IN TRANSIT.  THE RAMP SERVICEMAN WHO WAS UNLOADING THE PLANE GOT SOME OF THE FLUID ON HIS GLOVE.  HE LATER RUBBED HIS FACE AND EYES, WHICH CAUSED THEM TO START BURNING.  HE WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO AN OFFICE WHERE HIS EYES WERE WASHED OUT AND PARAMEDIC WERE CALLED TO LOOK AT HIM.  THE PACKAGE WAS TAKEN TO THE SMALL PACKAGE OFFICE WHERE THE CONSIGNEE WAS WAITING TO PICKUP THE PACKAGE.  WHEN ASKED WHAT WAS IN THE PACKAGE SHE STATED THAT IT WAS HOSE MEDICINE.  WHEN LOOKING AT THE BOTTLES INSIDE SHE SAID ONE OF THE BOTTLES CONTAINED CREOLAN AND THE OTHER PRO LIXEN.  I WAS FINALLY ABLE TO CONTACT THE CONSIGNEE DR. B. PAGE.  SHE TOLD ME THAT WHEN THE PACKAGE ARRIVED AT THE OFFICE SHE WOULD CALL ME TO TELL ME WHICH OF THE MEDICINES OR IF BOTH HAD BEEN BROKEN AND WERE LEAKING. AFTER THE PACKAGE GOT TO HER OFFICE SHE CALLED ME BACK TO TELL ME THAT IT WAS THE CREOLAN THAT HAD BROKEN WHICH SHE SAID IS CREOSOTE. WHEN I LOOKED THIS UP IN THE IATA DANGEROUS GOODS REGULATIONS BOOK I DISCOVERED THAT THIS IS A 6.1 TOXIC AND THAT IT IS NOT ALLOWED ON UNITED AIRLINES PLANES.  THE RAMP SERVICEMAN HURT WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL, SO I CALLED TO INFORM THE HOSPITAL WHAT THE ACTUAL CHEMICAL WAS.  THE DOCTOR AT THE HOSPITAL TOLD HIM THAT IF HE HAD INGEST ANY OF THIS CHEMICAL IT COULD HAVE BEEN FATAL TO HIM.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED HAD THE SHIPPER IN TUCSON PROPERLY PACKAGED THE FREIGHT AND DISCLOSED TO THE AGENT IN TUCSON WHAT HE WAS SHIPPING ON UNITED AIRLINES.  IF THIS HAD BEEN DONE UA WOULD HAVE REFUSED THE SHIPMENT DUE TO WE DO NOT ACCEPT THIS CHEMICAL ON OUR PLANES.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON MARCH 11, 1999 AT 2:30 P.M. BROWNING FERRIS INDUSTRIES OF NEW YORK, INC., (BFINY) WAS INVOLVED IN A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT. A TRACTOR (#105) PULLING A 28-FOOT PUP TRAILER (#102) WAS GOING SOUTHBOUND ON NEW YORK STATE THRUWAY (I-87).  THE VEHICLE WAS EN ROUTE FROM MERCY COMMUNITY HOSPITAL (140  HAMMOND STREET, PORT JERVIS, NY 12771) TO THE BFINY FACILITY (910 E. 138TH STREET, BRONX, NY 10454).  THE VEHICLE WAS TRANSPORTING REGULATED  MEDICAL WASTE IN THE FOLLOWING NON-BULK AND EXEMPT CONTAINERS:  WHITE MOP RINGER CO. - MWS30 REUSABLE PLASTIC CONTAINER - 30 GALLONS 4H2/35.6/S/99/USA/+AA2039.   WHITE MOP RINGER CO - MWS150, REUSABLE PLASTIC CONTAINER, 130 GALLONS DOT E 10826.  FIBER BOARD BOX 4.5 CF. DURING TRANSPORTATION, AND AANIMAL RAN ACROOS THE INTERSTATE.  IN AN ATTEMPT TO AVOID THE ANIMAL, THE BFI DRIVER REACTED TO MOVING TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD.  AT THIS POINT THE INTERSTATE CURVES TO THE LEFT.  THESE TWO FACTORS CAUSED THE TRAILER TO IMPACT THE GUARDRAIL ALON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE.  AFTER BOUNCING OVER THE RAIL, THE TRAILER CAME IN CONTACT WITH A TREE, WHERE IS RESTED AT ABOUT A 45-DEGREE ANGLE.   AT THIS ANGLE THREE (3) MWS30 REUSABLE PLASTIC CONTAINERS INVERTED WITHIN THE CONFINES OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 32 OUNCES OF SOME LIQUID WAS OBSERVED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TYPE OF SOURCE OF THE LIQUID IS UNKNOWN.  ALTHOUGH MOST OF THE LIQUID WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE VEHICLE A SMALL PORTION OF THE APPROXIMATE 32 OUNCES LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER.  BFI HAS TESTED AND RECEIVED CERTIFICATION FOR THE MWS30 CONTAINERS AT THE PACKING GROUP II LEVEL.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER PACKAGE USED IN THESE THREE CONTAINERS, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BAG USED WAS ONE THAT WAS PROVED BY THE CUSTOMER.  THEREFORE, PACKAGING INFORMATION, SPECIFICALLY TO THIS BAG, IS UNKNOWN.  BFI DOES PROVIDE COMPLIANT BAGS TO ITS CUSTOMERS; HOWEVER, FOR CUSTOMERS THAT WISH TO USE THERE OWN BAGS, BFI NOTIFIES THEM OF THE PACKAGING SPECIFICATIONS THAT THEY MUST COMPLY, SPECIFICALLY THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE INNER PACKAGING.   FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT, THE BFI DRIVER REPORTED GENERAL INFORMATION TO HIS OPERATING LOCATION VIA TELEPHONE.  IMMEDIATELY THE FACILITY'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, AS WELL AS THE MANAGEMENT TEAM, ARRIVED A THE SITE OF THE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  BFI EMPLOYEES, TRAINED IN PROPER EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND SPILL CLEAN - UP PROCEDURES, REMEDIED THE SPILL AND TRANSFERRED ALL CONTAINERS FROM THE DAMAGED PUP TRAILER TO A NEW VEHICLE.

SHIPMENT CAME IN ON REAR OF TRAILER.  STEEL WAS LOADED ON TOP OF PAILS.  DAMAGE WAS VIEWED.  SHIPMENT OF STEEL SHIFTED AND GOT PUNCTURED.  AREA WAS ISOLATED.  SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM.  BALANCE OF SHIPMENT WAS SENT ON TO DESTRUCTION.  DAMAGED SHIPMENT WAS SENT BACK TO SHIPPER.  SHIPPER GAVE AUTHORIZATION TO DOSE.  TRAILER WAS RED-TAGGED AND ISOLATED IN YAP.  BILL BUGLIO WAS CONTACTED FOR CLEANUP.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER,MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT ONTARIO. THE RAIL CUSTOMER HAD CALLED REPORTING THE ABOVE TANK CAR HAD BEEN SPOTTED TO THEIR PLANT OVER THE WEEKEND, AND WHEN INSPECTED THIS MORNING, NOTED A SMALL POOL (LESS THAN ONE PINT) OF PRODUCT ON THE PAVEMENT UNDER THE CAR. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE CUTOMERS ADDRESS AND NOTED THE TANK  CAR INSIDE  THE GATED LEAD TRACK AT THE REAR OF THE FACILITY.PLANT PERSONNEL HAD PLACED ABSORBENT OVER THE SPILL AREA, WHICH AMOUNTED TO ROUGHLY ONE SQUARE FOOT. A 5 GALLON BUCKET HAD BEEN PLACED UNDER THE BOTTLM OUTLET, WHICH CONTAINED LESS THAN A HALF PINT OF PRODUCT. INSPECTION OF THE CAR NOTED A DRIP EVERY 30 SECONDS. THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS FROM THE FLANGE ASSEMBLY THAT ATTACHES THE BOTTOM OUTLET TO THE BELLY OF THE CAR. ALL 8 OF THE SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. ACCESS TO THE BOLTS WAS RESTRICTED DUE TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET BEING PROTECTED BY AN ENCLOSED SKID PLATE. UTILIZING A CROWS FOOT WRENCH, LIMITED ACCESS WAS ABTAINED AND THE BOLTS TIGHTENED. THE BOTLS COULD NOT BE TORQUED TO THE MANUFACTURERS SPECIFICATIONS UTILIZING THE CROWS FOOT, HOWEVER, THE DRIP WAS GREATLY REDUCED. THIS FACILITY ONLY HAS A ONE CAR SPOT FOR OFF LOADING, AND IT WAS CURRENTLY OCCUPIED. PLANT PERSONNEL WERE ADVISED TO KEEP THE BUCKET UNDER THE CAR UNTIL IT COULD BE SPOTTED FOR OFF LOADING THE FOLLOWING DAY.EXXON WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED TO HAVE THE CAR INSPECTED UPON IT'S RETURN TO BAYTOWN. DUE TO MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, SPARKSS, NV, WAS NOTIFIED BY  RISK  MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER, ST LOUIS, MO, THAT TANK CAR UTLX 99114, ON SPOT COASTAL CHEMICAL, RENNOX NV WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS. UNION PACIFIC TRAFFIC MOVING EASTBOUND AND WESTBOUND  ON PAIRED TRACKAGE WAS STOPPED  ACCOUNT THE RELEASE. SUBSEQUENT INVESTGATION DEVELOPED THAT DURING UNLOADING A LEAK DEVELOPED FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE POINTED TOWARDS 'B' END OF TANK CAR INSIDE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. COASTAL CHEMICAL FORCES WERE ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK AND DISCOVERED THAT THE FEMALE THREADED FITTING THAT WAS SECURED TO LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE BY EIGHT (8) 3/8 INCH CAP SCREWS OUTSIDE WORKING INTERNAL MECHANISM OF THE VALVE WERE LOOSE. THIS THREADED FITTING RECEIVED THE UNLOADING NIPPLE  THAT EXTENDED THRU THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING TO ALLOW UNLOADING. THE THREE (3) TOP CAP SCREWS WERE LOOSE  ENOUGH THAT A GAP WAS VISIBLE BETWEEN VALVE AND FITTING. THE FIVE (5) REMAINING CAP SCREWS WERE LOOSE THAN FINGER TIGHT. WHEN COASTAL PERSONNEL MADE ENTRY INSIDE PROTECTIVE HOUSING THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY CLOSING THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE. COASTAL CHEMICAL CONTACTS WERE BOB HANFORD AND CURTIS HOLT, PHONE 775/6359100.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS IN THE ROPER YARD AND IN COMPANY WITH MR. RUSS KELLY FRA HAZ/MAT INSPECTOR, TANKCAR GATX74024 WAS FOUND TO HAVE A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISC. IT WAS A 165# ZOOK DISK, WITH THE SAFETY VENT MOUNTED ON THE MANWAY COVER. THE DISC WAS REPLACED IN KIND, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED. RMCC WAS NOTIFIED, AS WAS THE SHIPPER ELF ATOCHEM, ME BOB TYCE ADVISED OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES.

RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER, ST LOUIS, MO, NOTITIED REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, SPARKS NV THAT TANK CAR NATX 29068, SPOTTED IN TRACK NUMBER 5, LAS VEGAS ARDEN YARD WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP. WHITELEY VERIFIED THAT CAR WAS ISOLATED AND EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN ADVISED OF CONDITION AND WERE PROTECTED. WHITELEY CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE AT LAS VEGAS REQUESTING ASSISTANCE; HOWEVER, WAS TOLD THEIR POLICY PROHIBITED THEM  FROM ENTERING RAILROAD PROPERTY. CHEMTREC  NOTIFICATION RESULTED IN BILL BAKER MAKING CONTACT AND UPON EXPLANATION  OF CIRCUMSTANCEES HE ENTERED INTO AGREEMENT WITH JOHN BRADLEY, WATERS ENVIRONMENTAL, LAS VEGAS NV TO INSPECT TANK CAR. WHITELEY CONSULTED WITH BRADLEY AND HIS INSPECTION FOUND 10 BOLT HOLD DOWN ASSEMBLY ON LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WITH ALL BOLTS LOOSE 4 NOTEDMISSING. INTERNAL PRESSURE INSIDE TANK CAR WAS BLEND OFF, BOLTS SECURED, AND TANK CAR RELEASED FOR DELIVERY. COMBINATION HOUSING OVER LIQIUD VALVE WAS PROTECTED WITH  INTACT SEAL BF 1739 TLNA. CHEMTREC BEVERLY WAS FURNISHED ALL DETAILS.

column168: ON THURSDAY, 3/18/1999, TANK CAR UTLX 71118 WAS SET OUT TO THE KCS INTERCHANGE TRACK AT TIOGA, LA AT ABOUT 0935 HOURS THE CAR WAS INSPRCTED BY FRA HAZ MAT INSPECTOR JIM DUNCAN. DENCAN OBSERVED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM BENEATH THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. DUNCAN NOTIFIEDSENIOR SPECIAL AGENT JIM HERRING OF THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD AT ALEXANDRIA, LA HERRING CONTACTED THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER AND THE FOLLOWING NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE; TOM ROBINSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FILED OPERATIONS, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, CHEMTREC, KCS RR AND LUBRIZOL.ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS THE RESULT OF A DEFECTIVE MANWAY COVER PLATE GASKET. THE CAR WAS NOT LEAKING AS IT SAT MONTIONLESS. ROBINSON LEARNED THAT DUNCAN HAD ALSO FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISC TO BE, IN HIS OPINION, IN NONCOMPLIANCE RELATIVE TO IT BEING A 100 POUND DISC AS OPPOSED TO REQUIRED 165 POUND DISC. ROBINSON CONTACTED MR. GREG PERUN OF LUBRIZOL TO ARRANGE FOR REPLACEMENT OF THE DEFECTIVE GASKET AND THE FRANGIBLE DISC. PERUN CONSULTED WITH MR. BILL WESTBROOK OF MERICHEM.UNION TANK CAR COMPANY WAS CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED THEIR MOBIL REPAIR UNIT FROM BATON ROUGE LA. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT  THE TIOGA INTERCHANGE TRACKS UNTIL UNION TANK CAR COMPLETED THEIR WORK. UPON RESPONSE TO THE SCENE THE UNION TANK CAR TECHNICIANS WERE ABLE TO REPLACE THE DEFECTIVE GASKET, HOWEVER WERE NOT ABLE TO REPLACE THE FRANGIBLE DISC. AN EMERGENCY EXEMPTION WOULD BE SOUGHT FOR THE MOVEMENT OF THE CAR UNTO DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING. THE CAR WOULD THEN BE SHOPPED AND THE DISC REPLACED. ON FRIDAY,3/19/1999 LUBRIZOL OBTAINED EMERGENCY EXEMPTION FRA-9903070.

EACH DRUM HAD TWO CAPS AND AT LEAST ON EACH DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE WITH THE PRODUCT BY PASSING THE THREADS. THE CONTAINERS WERE RELOADED FOR HIHWAY MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: 2200 E/ 2300 N 1/4 MILE EAST AND 1/8 MILE SOUTH IN PRAIRIE TOWNSHIP WHICH IS IN EDGAR COUNTY ILLINOIS. THE CUSTOMER WAS APPLYING AMMONIA ON A 28.5 ACRE FIELD. THE TOOLBAR ADJUSTABLE HITCH PIN CAME OUT ON A TURN AND THE TANK CAME UNHOOKED. THE HOSE BROKE  IN TWO BECAUSE IT WAS AT A 90 DEGREE ANGLE. 5700 PUNDS OF AMMONIA WAS RELEASED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. ON THE TOOLBAR WHERE THE AMMONIA WAGON IS HITCHED UP THERE IS A COUPLING DEVICE THAT CAN BE RELEASED AND EXTENDED TO MAKE HOOKING UP THE AMMONIA WAGON EASIER. THE HITCH PIN ON THE TOOLBAR WAS NOT FULLY ENGAGED IN THE HOLE. WHEN THE TOOLBAR WAS TURNED AT THE END OF THE FIELD THE PLATE CAME OUT OF THE TOOLBAR. THE HOSE THAT WAS BROKEN RAN FROM THE NURSE WAGON TO THE TOOLBAR. THE PLACE THAT THE HOSE BROKE WAS RIGHT AT THE POINT WHERE THE COUPLING ON THE END OF THE HOSE MET THE HOSE ITSELF. THE HOSE WAS DUE TO BE REPLACED THIS YEAR. THE NURSE WAGON WAS HITCHED UP BY THE FARMER IN THE FIELD. THE PIONEER QUICK COUPLER ON THE TOOL BAR SWIVELED.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY FORCES REPORTING A LEAKING IM TANK ON THE INBOUND ( WESTBOUND) IEWLBB-21, LOCATED IN TRACK 805. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LOCATION AND OBSERVERED THE ABOVE IM TANK ON FLATCAR HS 902067. THE "VALVE" END OF THE TANK HAD A LARGE PRODUCT TRAIL EMITTING FROMM THE TOP AREA, DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE TANK, AS WELL AS A SMALL PRODUCT TRAIL DOWN THE CENTER SECTION OF THE TANK DIRECTLY BELOW THE MANWAY. INSPECTION DEVELPOED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AT THE " VALVE" END OF THE IM TANK WAS FROM THE VALVE COMPARTMENT ON THE TOP END OF TANK. THE 4 BOLTS ON THE LIQUID LINE FLANGE WERE LOOSE,AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. THE BALL VALVE FOR THE LIQUID LINE WAS ALSO OPEN APPROXIMATELY 1/8TH OF AN INCH DUE TO THE SPRING HANDLE BEING UNSECURED. THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE ALSO NOTED TO BE ONLY FINGER TIGHT, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE PAST THE MANWAY GASKET. ALL OF THE FREE STANDING PRODUCT IN THE VALVE AND MANWAY COMPARTMENTS WERE REMOVED TO PREVENT ANY FUTHER LOSS OF PRODUCT. THE LOOSE APERTURES WERE SECURED PRIOR TO MOVING THE TANK. THE TANK WAS THEN REMOVED FROM THE FLATCAR AND "DIAPERED" PRIOR TO BEING PLACED ONTO A CHASSIS ONCE THE PLASTIC SHEETING WAS SECURED TO THE TANK TO PREVENT ANY RELEASE OF PRODUCT,IT WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE SECURED AND ISOLATED. THE FLATCAR WAS THEN DECONTAMINATED AND THE EQUIPMENT RETURNED TO INTERMODAL OPERATIONS FOR REUSE. AS SOME OF  THE PRODUCT HAD CONTAINATED PORTIONS OF  THE INSULATION BETWEEN THE CLADDING AND THE TANK, IT WAS DETEMINED THAT TE AFFECTED INSULATION WOULD HAVE TO BE REMOVED. APPROXIMATELY ON HALF OF  THE CLADDING AND INSULATION WERE FOUND TO BE AFFECTED AND WERE ULTIMATELY REMOVED. THE BARE TANK AND FRAME WERE AGAIN DECONTAMINATED TO REMOVE ANY RESIDUAL OF THE PRODUCT. ARRANGEMENTS WILL BE MADE TO HAVE NEW IN STULATION AND CLADDING INSTALLED PRIOR TO MOVING THE TANK ONTO DESTINATION.

column168: EMG MANAGER, CHRISTINE CHRISTMAS WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC THAT FIVE TANK CAR LOADS OF ASPHALT WERE DERAILED ON THE SANTA ANA BRANCH AT BLOOMFIELD ROAD AND DEL AMO BLVD. MANAGER CHRISTMAS CONTACTED TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL AND ADVISED THEM TO MEET HER AT THE SITE. UPON ARRIVAL, MANAGER CHRISTMAS MET THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM. SHE WALKED THE DERAILMENT WITH GARY BROUGHER OF THE LA HAZMAT TEAM AND THEY OBSERVED A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS NEAR TANK CAR GATX 50853. THE ASPHALT WAS COOLING AND HARDENDING QUICKLY, SO IT WAS NOT NECESSARY TO IMPLEMENT ANY CONTAINMENT MEASURES. THE CONDITION OF THE FIVE CARS AND RERAILING ACTIVITIES WAS DISCUSSED WITH PAUL PEREZ, MGR MECH, MNTCE, RON SANTAN , MGR. TRACK MNTCE, AND OSCAR LUEVANO, WRECKER FOREMAN. MR. PEREZ ADVISED THAT THE CARS COULD BE UPRIGHTED AND MOVED WITHOUT NEEDING  TO BE TRANSLOADED  FIRST. SINCE TRACK WORK COULD NOT BE STARTED UNTIL THE FOLLOWING MORNING, THE SITE WAS SECURED FOR THE NIGHT, AND A REPRESENTATIVE OF TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL REMAINED ON SITE THROUGHOUT THE NIGHT. TRACK WORK WAS BEGUN THE NEXT MORNING, WITH REPRESENTATIVES FROM PARAMOUNT PETROLEUM ( DAN BRIGGS, WES OWENS STEVEN FRARKAS, AND DAVE DRAGT) ONSITE. THEY ADVISD THEY WOULD TAKE THE MATERIAL BACK AT THEIR PLANT (FIVE MILES AWAY),BUT THEY DID NOT HAVE ROOM TO TAKE IT BACK IN RAILCARS. THE PLAN WAS TO FINISH RERAILING THE CARS THAT DAY AND THE NEXT DAY MOVE THEM EITHER TO PARAMOUNT OR TO THE ANAHEIM YARD FOR TRANSLOADING. TRANSLOAD OPERATIONS WERE SCHEDULED FOR THE FOLLOWING WEEK. ALL 5 OF THE DAMAGED CARS WERE MOVED TO ANAHEIM WHERE THEY COULD BE PLUMBED FOR STEAM TO REHEAT THE ASPHALT. MANAGER COOPER WORKED WITH TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL ON PREPARING THE CARS FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER. ON THURSDAY, APRIL 8TH, GATX 50853 WAS TRANSFERRED TO GATX 14164. ON FRIDAY, 9TH, RTCX 237202 WAS TRANSFERED TO ULTX 75638. ON MONDAY, APRIL 12TH, GATX 42251 WAS TRANSFERRED TO GATX 22881. ON THURSDAY, APRIL 15TH, UTLX 643942 WAS TRANSFERRED TO UTLX 643935, AND UTLX 71226 WAS TRANSFERRED  UTLX 643797. ALL OF THE BILLING WAS SWITCHED TO THE NEW CARS, AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE. THE DAMAGED CARS WERE TO BE LOADED ONTO FLATCARS FOR MOVEMENT TO CAR REPAIR FACILITIES.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER WHITELEY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING IM TANK AT THE ICTF, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA. TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO INSPECT THE IM TANK, AND IDENTIFIED THE RESOUCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE MANWAY. THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE EASILY TURNED BY HAND. THE MANWAY WAS OPENED TO INSPECT THE GASKET, WHICH WAS FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. THE MANWAY WAS THEN PROPERLY SECURED. THE PRODUCT RESIDUE CONTAINED INSIDE THE SPILL BOX  WAS REMOVED, THE AREA CLEANED, AND THE OVERFLOW TUBING FLUSHED  TO REMOVE ANY RESIDUAL. THE TANK WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ENSURE THE MANWAY WAS PROPERLY SECURED. THE TANK WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

I RESPONDED TO SPILL ON MT.KISCO BELT. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN. RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN HAD ME CLEAN UP ALL SPILLED SOLID MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED INTO A LINE SPILL TRAY. NO ABSORBENT WAS USED. PACKAGE WAS THEN PROCESSED IN THE DMP AREA. BETTER PACKING COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS SPILL.

MGR CTS WILDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM CAR FOREMAN KEN ENGLAND THA A EMPLOYEE REPORTED BECOMING ILL WHILE WORKING NEXT TO TANKCAR GATX 51318 UPON SPECTION IT WAS FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY TIGHTEN, CAUSING THE TOP MANWWAY COVER GASKET TO FAIL. MGR WILDER REPLACED THE GASKET. ADDITIONALLY, REPAIRS WERE NEEDED TO SAFETY APPLICANCES ON THE TANK CAR, WHICH WOUDL NECESSITATE TRANSFER OF THE LOAD PRIOR TO REPAIRS. THE EMPLOYEE SUFFERED NO RESIDUAL EFFECTS AND STAYED AT WORK. MGR WILDER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, ABITIBI- CONSOLIDATED OF CANADA AND ARRANGEMENTS WHERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE CAR. NO WATER WAYS OR DRAINS INVOLVED.

column168: MGR. WILDER WAS ADVISED THAT TANK CONTAINER UTCU 455610 WAS LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID. UPON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION MGR. WILDER FOUND THAT ABOUT 1/2 PINT OF LIQUID HAD SPILLED ON THE REAR RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCK THAT WAS TRANSPORTING THE CONTAINER INTO THE GLOBAL 1 FACILITY. IT WAS FOUND THAT THE TOP INLET COVER HAD NOT BEEN SECURED CORRECTLY AND THAT THERE WHERE TWO BOLTS ON THE TOP MANWAY COVER THAT HAD TO BE TIGHTENED BOUT 1/4 TURN EACH. MGR WILDER CHECKED ALL INLET AND OUTLET VALVES AND PROPERLY SEALED AND CLOSED THEM. THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF THE INLET VENT BEING LEFT OPEN DURING LOADING. THE TUCK DRIVER HAD ALREADY CLEANED THE SIDE  OF THE TRUCK. NO PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE GROUND AND NO WATER WAYS OR DRAINS INVOLVED.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: THE DRIVER, DAVID LOMAX, WAS MAKING MULTIPLE DELIVERIES.  WHILE MOVING THE FREIGHT THAT SPILLED, LOMAX DROPPED THE PAIL.  THE CONTENTS SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOORING AND LOMAX WAS OVERCOME BY THE PROLONGED EXPOSURE FROM THE FUMES COMING FROM THE LIQUID.  LOMAX TRANSPORTED TO HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  GALLATIN FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO SPILL, AND ABSORBED THE LIQUID WITH SAND.  THE SAND WAS RECOVERED IN 35 GALLON DRUM AND TRANSPORTED TO MXI ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES IN ABINGTON, VA FOR THERMAL TREATMENT.  THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE.  IT WAS BELIEVED THAT A DOT F5800.1 WAS SUBMITTED IN APRIL, 1999, BUT A COPY OF THAT FORM COULD NOT BE LOCATED.
